Place: Lower Trenta valley, between villages Soƒça and Trenta; right bank of river Soƒça, upstream entrance in a small river gorge between farmhouses Otokar, Trenta 4 and Matev≈æ, Trenta 1; East Julian Alps, Posoƒçje, Slovenia EC.

Comments: Flammulina elastica is a beautiful, winter growing species very similar to well-known and common Velvet Shank (Flammulina velutipes). The name Flammulina is based on the yellow-orange caps, which shine like little flames in the murky winter colored habitats. It is a rather newly separated species (1999). Several differences in the morphology between Flammulina velutipes and Flammulina elastica (however, very variable) are described in literature, but many, if not most of, authors consider both species indistinguishable solely on morphology. Only DNA analyses, sexual incompatibility and spore shape (particularly Q) and dimensions (mostly their length) separate them.

Currently Flammulina elastica appears a rare species in Slovenia and elsewhere. It is not included neither in the Boletus Informaticus data base (Ref.: 6) nor in the Operational List of Fungi of Slovenia (Ref. 7). Because Flammulina elastica cannot be separated from Flammulina velutipes in field without microscopy, hundreds of historical field observations of the latter can actually be the former. Therefore, published distribution maps of both species seem questionable.

More than 15 pilei were observed on the trunk from 30 cm above to about 2 m above the ground, most of them were old and hence of very dark color. Pilei diameter 4 – 7.5 cm, stipe length 2.8 – 4 and their diameter 0.5 – 1.4 cm; stipe pliant, firm, like made of soft rubber; SP abundant, white, oac909. Photographed in frozen state.

With average (at N=44) spore length 9.1 ¬µm, about 25% of spores longer than 10 ¬µm instead of ‘a few only’ for Flammulina velutipes according to (Ref.: 5) and Qe = 2.6 this determination seems quite reliable.

My impression was: distinct, hard to say on what, but not unpleasant. This contradicts to most descriptions found in literature available to me. While its taste is described quite consistently as unpleasant and bitter (such was also my observation), the descriptions of its smell vary wildly. In the literature one can find following statements: unpleasant, on chicken run, on wet chicken, on chicken house, on roses, on honey, sweet-rancid, strongly sourish, stale‚Ä¶ Apparently all other traits of this find fit well to the descriptions of this species.

Growing scattered, more than 10 pilei on a few square meters of forest ground; pilei diameter 3 ‚Äì 6 cm, stipe length 3 ‚Äì 5 cm, stipe diameter 4 ‚Äì 8.5 mm, hollow, fibrous; a lot of mycelium at the base of the stipe among rotten leaves; SP white, oac900.
Clitocybe phaeophthalma is presently (Dec. 2019) a current name according to Index Fungorum as well as according to Mycobank.

A Muscle alignment of Amanita sp. sp-N46 RET 319-5 MN820545 with sequences of five AZ collections that are genetically similar appear to indicate that there are two closely related AZ groups—an idea supported by the phylogenetic tree. The genetic distance between Group 1 sequences, MT232417 and MT382639, and Amanita sp. sp-N46 RET 319-5 MN820545 may be as low as .25-.30%. RET reviewed my alignment and made the following comment: “Hence, Group 1 may be interpreted as having only one column treated as a MAYBE difference. With more data you could build a
case for identity; however, I think you have a very good case for two SNPs which
could be treated as no problem for arguing for a single species.”
